Accessing gk_central snapshot
 

To access the (future) curation graph database via Neo4j MCP installed locally at your own computer (see above), you may use ssh tunneling by following the following steps:

1). Set up ssh tunneling: 

ssh -i ~/.ssh/your_key.pem -L 7687:localhost:7687 user@curator.reactome.org 

Note: replace “user” with your own account name, your_key.pem with your own identity file. The first number is the port at your own computer, this may change to whatever you like. The second is the port at curator.reactome.org. Don’t change it. Make sure this is running always. You may try different ways to set it up. Please consult with AI.

2). If you are using cluade code, add the following configuration into the project folder (e.g. reactome-curator-workflows):

{
"mcpServers": {
"neo4j-mcp": {
"type": "stdio",
"command": "neo4j-mcp",
"args": [],
"env": {
"NEO4J_URI": "bolt://localhost:7688",
"NEO4J_USERNAME": "neo4j",
"NEO4J_PASSWORD": “{I will send you the password}",
"NEO4J_DATABASE": "graph.db",
"NEO4J_READ_ONLY": "true"
}
}
}
}

The above should be in a file called .mcp.json. You can add it directly by following the instruction from Claude Code.

3). Yes, make sure you have installed neo4j-mcp already and add it into your PATH.

4). Check mcp list to make sure the mcp is installed correctly, and then ask anything about our database.

Some important points:

The schemas are different for gk_central and the public Reactome mirror. How will Claude know to use the appropriate (complete) schema for gk_central queries?

Here's the issue: when I call reactome_cypher_schema, it queries whichever server that tool is bound to. In this session I happened to call reactome:reactome_cypher_schema (the public mirror) rather than gk-central:reactome_cypher_schema, so the schema I had in context was the public one. I then had to do exploratory queries against gk-central to discover things like:

The stableIdentifier relationship (not present in the public mirror)
The released boolean property on StableIdentifier nodes
The reverse direction of the created relationship

If I had relied solely on the public schema, I would have written incorrect Cypher from the start.
What I should do going forward: whenever a question is clearly directed at gk-central, I should call gk-central:reactome_cypher_schema first, before writing any queries. The two databases differ in meaningful ways:

gk-central has curation-specific nodes/properties (StableIdentifier.released, doRelease on events, etc.)
Relationship directions can differ
Properties present in one may be absent or null in the other

So the safe habit is: match the schema call to the target database. I'll make sure to do that explicitly rather than defaulting to the public mirror's schema. Thanks for flagging it — it's an easy mistake to make silently.


